# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1913-new-york-giants-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1913-new-york-giants-season] The **1913 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 31st season.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1913-new-york-giants-season] It involved the Giants winning the National League pennant for the third consecutive year.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1913-new-york-giants-season] Led by manager John McGraw, the Giants dominated the NL and finished 12½ games in front of the second place Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1913-new-york-giants-season] They were beaten by the Philadelphia Athletics in the World Series.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1913-new-york-giants-season] Ace pitcher Christy Mathewson went 25–11 and led the NL with a 2.06 ERA.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1913-new-york-giants-season] Rube Marquard and Jeff Tesreau also won over 20 games, and the Giants easily allowed the fewest runs of any team in the league.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1913-new-york-giants-season] Taken together with the 1911 and 1912 pennant winners, this team is considered one of the greatest of all-time.
[src:1913-new-york-giants-season/1913-new-york-giants-season] The roster was basically unchanged from 1912.
